WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.520
Welcome to the Test Set. Here we talk with some of the brightest thinkers and tinkerers

00:00:06.520 --> 00:00:11.560
in statistical analysis, scientific computing, and machine learning. Digging into what makes

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:16.879
them tick, plus the insights, experiments, and OMG moments that shape the field.

00:00:16.879 --> 00:00:25.000
Wes McKinney Hi everyone, I'm Wes McKinney, Principal Architect at Posit and co-host on

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:32.080
the Test Set podcast. A little while ago, we recorded and released a number of interviews

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:37.240
where Michael Chow was the host. I was interviewed along with Hadley Wickham, Roger Pang, and

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:45.880
Meena Set and Kaya Rundle. We wanted to turn the tables and interview Michael so you can

00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:53.759
learn more about him as we continue to build and produce this podcast. Michael Chow is

00:00:53.759 --> 00:00:59.000
a Principal Software Engineer at Posit and a key contributor to the Python community.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.919
He received a PhD in Cognitive Psychology from Princeton University and is interested

00:01:03.919 --> 00:01:08.959
in what drives expert data science performance. This led him to build Datacamp's Signal Adaptive

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:14.620
Test of Data Science Skill. So I'll turn it over to you, Michael, to give a little brief

00:01:14.620 --> 00:01:21.199
intro to yourself and your career up until this point, and then we'll dive into all of

00:01:21.199 --> 00:01:25.639
the things that make you tick and the things that you're thinking about these days. I've

00:01:25.639 --> 00:01:31.040
got a lot on my mind with everything that's going on with AI, so I'm sure we have a lot

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:32.040
to talk about.

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:37.800
Michael Chow Yeah, excited for the inevitable AI blurb.

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:44.680
And I have to say, as a person who works full-time on Python, open source at Posit, formerly

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:48.959
our studio, I'm a giant fan of all your work in Python, so I'm excited to be able to talk

00:01:48.959 --> 00:01:56.599
about just all data, but also what's going on in the Python ecosystem. I guess as a little

00:01:56.599 --> 00:02:04.360
background, yeah, so I did a PhD in Cognitive Psychology, and I would say a few years in,

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:10.559
I sort of realized that I wasn't sure if I wanted to fight tooth and claw for an academic

00:02:10.559 --> 00:02:19.880
position, so I started to do way more Python and R for data analysis. And then, yeah, after

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:24.679
graduating, was able to go to data camp where I worked on sort of how do we grade people's

00:02:24.679 --> 00:02:32.119
submissions and how do instructors who are writing these interactive exercises write

00:02:32.119 --> 00:02:38.679
code to grade other people's code that they submit for these exercises? So very meta-activity.

00:02:38.679 --> 00:02:49.600
Yeah, so basically, from there, did a lot more data science into how people learn sort

00:02:49.600 --> 00:02:58.440
of on this interactive platform, and that sort of led me into, like, how do I best analyze

00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:04.440
in Python and R? And then finally, I guess, took me to Posit where I'm really excited

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:11.279
to work on open source tools around data analysis and to be able to think about what are the

00:03:11.279 --> 00:03:19.240
sort of nicest things we could do during data analysis to kind of speed people up or help

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:24.919
them kind of go end-to-end from raw data to some kind of report or insight.

00:03:24.919 --> 00:03:30.720
It's interesting because I found in our field of open source data science tool builders

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:36.800
that there's a lot of people who started out in a scientific field. So cognitive psychology

